<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LatAm Leaders Discuss Capital Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Diplomats worked feverishly  
Saturday to break an impasse over language on regulating the 
international flow of capital in advance of a summit of Latin 
American, Caribbean and European leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil and Chile have pressed hard to include wording on capital  
controls in the Declaration of Rio de Janeiro to be signed at a 
two-day summit starting Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil was among the hardest hit by the financial crisis that  
swept from Asia two years ago, and argues that making it harder for 
capital to jump from country to country would reduce the world 
economy's volatility and curb the spread of crises. 
</P>
<P>
	The respected O Globo of Rio newspaper reported Saturday that a  
section on capital flow would be part of the summit's final 
declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brazilian Foreign Ministry sources were unclear. Spokesman  
Jose Alfredo Graca Lima said it might be included. But another 
ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it 
would not be. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, diplomats said the overall declaration was nearly  
complete. The document is expected to cover a wide range of topics, 
from human rights to terrorism, illegal drugs and free trade. 
</P>
<P>
	They resumed work Saturday at Rio's Museum of Modern Art, the  
site of the summit, to complete a draft declaration for a meeting 
of foreign ministers on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the final document contains broad, nonbinding language  
on capital controls, the mere mention would be a victory for 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a reference ``would express the concern of Europe to which  
this capital submits entire economies around the world,'' Francisco 
Gomes, Latin American director for the European Commission, was 
quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	After Thailand's economy crashed in 1997 and started a global  
panic, investors pulled their money out of emerging markets, 
including Brazil. The government lost $10 billion literally 
overnight and decreed a series of spending cuts and tax increases 
that slowed the economy to a crawl. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the growing fear among investors that Brazil would  
default on debt payments prompted another run on the Brazilian 
currency, the real. The government was forced to devalue the real, 
which plunged 45 percent before recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	President Fernando Henrique Cardoso has proposed a  
``redesigning'' of the global financial system to make it more 
difficult for capital to jump around. Germany, Portugal and Spain 
reportedly have been sympathetic to the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Another proposal is the so-called ``Tobin Tax,'' which would be  
a duty on financial operations with the income earmarked for a fund 
to help economies in crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the agenda are a proposal to start talks about a free  
trade zone linking the European Union and Mercosur, the South 
American trade bloc that comprises Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, 
Paraguay and associated members Chile and Bolivia. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the expected agreement on trade talks was hailed as a  
victory, EU Vice President Manuel Marin said Saturday there is no 
deadline for the talks to start or end. It was widely reported that 
the talks would start in 2001 and conclude by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	The first leader to arrive in Rio on Saturday was Mexican  
President Ernesto Zedillo, who was scheduled to have lunch with 
Cardoso on Sunday. The others are expected Sunday and Monday 
morning. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
