<DOCNO> APW19990626.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 03:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elite Class Within Inkster's Reach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Juli Inkster wants to ride this wave as  
long as it will last. If she can stay on top for two more rounds in 
the LPGA Championship, it might carry her all the way to the Hall 
of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	That seemed like a long shot at the start of the year, her 16th  
season on the LPGA Tour. She had 17 victories, three of them 
majors, but was lost in the hype over younger stars like Se Ri Pak, 
Karrie Webb and Annika Sorenstam. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Inkster could be 36 holes away from joining a really elite  
class. 
</P>
<P>
	Inkster had a 5-under-par 66 on Friday, giving her a four-way  
share of the lead in her bid to become only the second woman to win 
the LPGA's modern career Grand Slam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who knows what can happen?'' she said. ``I just want a chance  
come Sunday to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her bogey-free round on the DuPont Country Club course was her  
15th round under par since the Chick-fil-A Charity Championship the 
last week in April. The U.S. Open was her third victory of the 
year, and she returned two weeks later to finish third in the 
Shoprite Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is probably going to be some point when I hit the  
wall,'' Inkster said. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't look that way on a breezy, cloudy Friday afternoon.  
Inkster finished the day at 8-under 134, tied with Liselotte 
Neumann (67), Jenny Lidback (67) and Cristie Kerr, whose 64 tied 
the course record for the LPGA Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	With 36 holes left, anything can happen.  
</P>
<P>
	Kelli Kuehne, the 22-year-old Texan who gave Inkster a spirited  
challenge in the U.S. Open, continued her amazing run with a 67 and 
was one stroke behind. Two-time LPGA champion Laura Davies isn't 
getting much out of her putter, but she still managed an even-par 
71 and was only two strokes back at 136. Pak, the defending 
champion, was at 137. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would love a shot come Sunday,'' Inkster said. ``But there's  
a lot of time between now and then. There's a lot of good players 
behind me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inkster needs only three points to qualify for the Hall of Fame.  
She could pick up two by winning a major championship this week, 
and her second major of the year could help her lead to another 
point if she won player of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The real challenge in the Grand Slam. Only Pat Bradley has won  
the Dinah Shore, U.S. Open, LPGA Championship and the du Maurier 
Classic in a career. Mickey Wright also won the Grand Slam when it 
consisted of the Open, LPGA, Titleholders and Western Open from 
1955-1966. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not on my mind right now,'' Inkster said. ``There's a lot  
of golf left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not for Karrie Webb. Her modern record of 16 consecutive top-10s  
came crashing to a halt on Friday when she recorded another 1-over 
72 and missed the cut by one stroke. It was the first time Webb 
missed the cut in 33 tournaments, dating to the Standard Register 
Ping in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never really played well here before,'' Webb said. ``It's  
not the course's fault, I just don't feel comfortable on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inkster made birdie on two of the first three holes with 15-foot  
putts, then held it together by saving par from the bunker with an 
8-foot putt. She joined the leaders with a 7-iron to 20 feet on No. 
17 for her fifth birdie of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I'm doing differently, but it just all seems  
to be working,'' Inkster said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inkster was in about the same position three weeks ago after two  
rounds of the U.S. Open at Old Waverly -- tied for the lead after 
the second round, with several players close on her heels. She had 
a 67 in the third round and wound up winning by five strokes. 
</P>
<P>
	``All it takes is one hot person,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Maybe Kuehne will be up to the challenge this time. She was  
paired with Inkster in the final round at Old Waverly and put a 
scare into her by looking at eight birdie putts on the front nine, 
but making only one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	If Inkster is the hottest player in women's golf, Kuehne isn't  
too far behind. Once she jump-started her season -- her career, for 
that matter -- during an important swing through Texas, Kuehne has 
been living up to her billing as the female version of Tiger Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	She won the LPGA Corning Classic. She nearly won the Open. And  
here she is again, whistling and singing and belting it down the 
middle, making all the important putts and most of her birdie 
chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a whole lot more relaxed this year,'' Kuehne said. ``I  
think that's pretty evident.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
