<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 03:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia, NATO Planes Due in Pristina  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO and Russian troops prepared  
today for the first arrival of flights at the Pristina airport 
since peacekeepers began deploying in Kosovo two weeks ago. Two 
planes were expected about noon: a Russian transport carrying an 
advance team of paratroopers and technicians and a NATO plane with 
air traffic control equipment. About 200 Russian troops seized the 
airport June 12, beating NATO into the province by hours and 
forcing protracted negotiations on Russia's role in the 
peacekeeping mission. Russia plans to send 3,600 more troops. 

</P>
<P>
	China Immigration Ruling Draws Fire  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's legislature ruled today that a Hong Kong  
court violated the territory's constitution by not consulting 
Chinese lawmakers before deciding a case concerning China's state 
affairs. The dispute underscored tensions between authoritarian 
China and freewheeling Hong Kong. Opponents feared the case -- 
ostensibly about immigratio -- would undermine the autonomy and 
judicial independence Beijing promised the territory after 
regaining control from Britain nearly two years ago. Hundreds of 
people, many mainland Chinese without residency permits, gathered 
outside government offices in protest. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Creating Spy Hunting Division  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Bureau of Investigation is proposing  
to create a division devoted solely to hunting spies, part of a 
government-wide review of counterintelligence, The New York Times 
reported today. The move comes amid suspicions that China stole 
nuclear secrets for two decades. American intelligence agencies 
have increasingly focused on threats of terrorism, causing 
counterintelligence efforts to dwindle, the newspaper said, citing 
unidentified government officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Capture First NBA Title  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs captured their first  
National Basketball Association championship last night with a 
78-77 victory over the New York Knicks, who missed a final shot at 
the buzzer. Avery Johnson made a shot from the corner to put the 
Spurs ahead by one point with 47 seconds left in Game 5 in the 
best-of-seven series. But the title wasn't assured until the Knicks 
failed to score on the game's final play, an inbounds pass from 
Charlie Ward that found Latrell Sprewell too far under the basket. 
His awkward shot missed, and the Spurs stormed the court to 
celebrate. 

</P>
<P>
	S. Korea, N. Korea Resume Talks  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- North Korea and South Korea briefly resumed talks  
today, trading views on the detention of a tourist, reuniting 
families separated in their bitter 54-year rivalry and a naval 
skirmish that broke up the talks four days ago. Although it was 
unclear if any progress was made, prospects for the talks -- the 
highest level contacts between the governments in 14 months -- 
improved with North Korea's release Friday of a South Korean 
tourist detained for six days. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Cadet Sacked on Sex Charge  
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Virginia Military Institute's top cadet  
was dismissed last month for allegedly demanding sex from three 
freshmen women, the Richmond Times-Dispatch reported Saturday. VMI 
officials told the newspaper that Jerry Webb II was expelled for 
conduct unbecoming a cadet. Sources the newspaper did not identify 
said the misconduct involved demands for sex from the three women. 
The newspaper was unable to reach Webb for comment. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Soldiers Killed in Indonesia  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Separatist rebels killed two soldiers  
and wounded at least four civilians in three attacks in Aceh 
province, the military and the official Antara news agency said 
today. Violence has heightened in recent weeks in Aceh, a province 
1,100 miles northwest of Jakarta. At least 10 people, including a 
soldier, were killed earlier this week as a rebel band intensified 
a campaign for a separate Islamic state, police and witnesses said. 

</P>
<P>
	Jimenez Hurls No-Hitter for Cards  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Jose Jimenez, a rookie right-hander suffering  
through one of the worst seasons of any National League pitcher, 
threw the first St. Louis no-hitter in 16 years last night, 
outdueling Randy Johnson in the Cardinals' 1-0 victory over the 
Arizona Diamondbacks. Jimenez also became the first rookie to pitch 
a no-hitter since Wilson Alvarez of the Chicago White Sox on Aug. 
11, 1991. Jimenez (4-7) struck out seven, walked two and hit a 
batter. No Arizona runner got beyond second base. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
