<DOCNO> APW19990626.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 19:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden 2, Ghana 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sweden earned its way to the quarterfinals of the  
women's World Cup. Next is its biggest challenge -- defending 
champion and neighboring rival Norway. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal was to get to the quarterfinals. Now we've done that  
and I think we'll meet Norway. This time we're going to win that 
game,'' Victoria Svensson said Saturday after her two second-half 
goals led a 2-0 victory over scrappy and physical Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	Norway has won the last seven meetings with Sweden, including a  
semifinal win in the 1991 World Cup. The teams will meet again 
Wednesday in San Jose, Calif. Norway ran its record in this year's 
tournament to 3-0 by routing Japan 4-0 Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been several years and now we're closer than we've ever  
been. We played them in the Algarve Cup and it was closer than it's 
ever been,'' Sweden coach Marika Domanski Lyfors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Svensson scored on a header in the 58th minute Saturday, taking  
Malin Mostrom's crossing pass from the right corner and beating 
goalkeeper Memunatu Sulemana to put Sweden ahead 1-0. 
</P>
<P>
	The score came with Ghana one player down as defender Patience  
Sackey nursed an injury on the far sideline. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first I thought, `It's going to go over the goal.' Then I  
saw it and I was really happy because I missed a lot of chances in 
the first half,'' Svensson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana, in its first World Cup, just missed tying the game in the  
86th minute. As Swedish goalie Ulrika Karlsson tried to clear after 
a pass back from teammate Asa Lonnqvist, a sliding Elizabeth Baidu 
of Ghana blocked her kick and the ball deflected off the cross bar. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Black Queens stunned by their near-miss, Svensson raced  
to the other end, took a pass from Malin Gustafsson and scored 
again seconds later to make it 2-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed. We didn't deserve to lose,'' Ghana  
coach E.K. Afranie said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also disagreed with the labeling of his team as overly  
``physical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Soccer is a contact sport. When you talk about physical play,  
people make up their minds before we step on the field,'' he said. 
``People already think that African teams play physical, so their 
minds are already made up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The final minutes were played in a driving rain as a  
thunderstorm socked and soaked a crowd of 34,256 gathered for a 
doubleheader at Soldier Field, the largest for a twin bill so far 
not involving the host U.S. team. On Thursday night, a crowd of 
65,080 watched the United States defeat Nigeria on the same field. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Svensson's first goal, Sweden missed a chance for a  
two-goal lead after Stella Quartey was called for a foul against on 
Svensson in the penalty area and the Swedes were awarded a penalty 
kick. But Sulemana miraculously stopped the penalty shot by Malin 
Andersson as well as a quick rebound attempt seconds later by 
Therese Lundin. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden, a loser in the World Cup quarters four years ago, is  
2-1-0 in Group D. Ghana is 0-2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden midfielder Hanna Ljungberg, who scored two goals in an  
earlier victory over Australia, left in the sixth minute with a 
right knee injury that could keep her out of the rest of the 
tournament. She was scheduled to undergo an MRI and was replaced by 
Lundin. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana played without two starters. Defender Regina Ansah had  
been red carded in the previous game against China and defender 
Rita Yeboah had been assessed yellow cards in the Black Queens' 
previous two games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 06:46:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Outage Delays Mets-Braves Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The opener of a three-game series between the New  
York Mets and Atlanta Braves was delayed 45 minutes Friday night 
when an electrical problem knocked out a section of lights at 
Turner Field. 
</P>
<P>
	The malfunction apparently occurred less than two hours before  
the scheduled 7:40 p.m. start, affecting a section of lights that 
hover above the upper deck on the right-field side. 
</P>
<P>
	Power remained on for the rest of the 49,000-seat stadium, where  
a sellout was expected as the Braves, leading the NL East by three 
games over New York, tried to hold off the streaking Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	An announcement was made to the crowd about five minutes before  
the scheduled first pitch. There was little reaction as fans sat 
patiently in their seats or milled about the concourse beyond the 
center-field scoreboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just can't play a game,'' Braves president Stan Kasten  
joked. ``Everything else is working fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 7:45, the lights began to illuminate against the darkening  
sky, eliciting cheers from the crowd. Odalis Perez made the first 
pitch to Ricky Henderson at 8:25. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time in nearly six years that a Braves home  
game was delayed for reasons other than inclement weather. On July 
18, 1993, a press box fire at the old Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium 
held up the start of a game for about two hours. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 4 this season, a problem with the lights at Kansas  
City's Kauffman Stadium caused a game between the Royals and 
Cincinnati Reds to be postponed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 06:46:01 </DATE_TIME>
