<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 07:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers Facing Seats Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three car owners have filed a lawsuit against  
the nation's top automakers, alleging that seats in several makes 
of cars are defective and dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs also accused the automakers -- DaimlerChrysler AG,  
Ford Motor Co., General Motors Corp., and Saturn, a wholly owned 
subsidiary of GM -- of knowing that the seats were unsafe but doing 
nothing to fix them because of cost, according to papers filed 
Thursday in Manhattan's State Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs, who are seeking class-action status, say in  
court papers that the defect is a single recliner mechanism in 
about 1 million cars that causes a seat to collapse backward if the 
car is hit in the rear. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each seat is defective and unreasonably dangerous because it  
is unstable and susceptible to rearward collapse in the event of a 
rear-end collision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed by three New York state residents who own  
cars made with the allegedly defective seats. Their lawyers said 
they have a 1995 Geo Metro seat as an exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs, Linda Frank of North Merrick, Joshua Horstein of  
Manhattan, and Ross Kass of Syosset, are asking for compensatory 
damages, measured by the cost of fixing the defect, not to exceed 
$5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of the suit to the automakers could skyrocket to $5  
billion if each of the 1 million cars allegedly made with the 
defective seats is included in the class action. 
</P>
<P>
	GM spokesman Terry Rhadigan said the lawsuit had no basis.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is another example of frivolous lawsuit, where a large  
number of vehicle owners form a class when nothing is wrong with 
their vehicles,'' Rhadigan said. ``There's nothing wrong with the 
vehicles and there's nothing wrong with our seats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokesman Jim Cain said Ford will fight the lawsuit. He  
said the seats are designed to yield because testing proves it 
protects passengers from serious spinal injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The other automakers could not immediately be reached for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in court papers is a March letter from Saturn  
suggesting that its customers come in and get the seat fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Saturn issued a recall of 136,300 cars because their  
seat backs could recline or collapse suddenly. 
</P>
<P>
	The gear teeth on the reclining mechanisms of driver and front  
passenger seats in 1994 and 1995 models were to blame, the National 
Highway Traffic Safety Administration said at the time. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 05:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singer Gosdin Recovers From Stroke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Award-winning country music singer Vern  
Gosdin is recovering from his second stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	The 64-year-old singer, whose hits include ``Chiseled in  
Stone,'' ``Set 'em Up Joe'' and ``I Can Tell by the Way You 
Dance,'' suffered the stroke on Wednesday while driving home. He 
remained hospitalized Friday, but his manager, Lacey Lynne, said 
the singer was ``doing great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gosdin suffered paralysis on his left side after his first  
stroke in 1995. No further paralysis resulted from the recent 
stroke, and doctors expect Gosdin to return home in up to three 
days, Lynne said. 
</P>
<P>
	``All his limbs are in working condition,'' she said. ``He's  
just as ornery as he was before he went in. He's giving everybody a 
hard time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
