<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lopsided Results Mark Cup Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) -- While most of the coaches in the Women's  
World Cup proclaimed the competition would be even, skeptics 
pointed to the apparent discrepancy in talent from top to bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle games of the opening round, which concludes this  
weekend, it was obvious who the ``haves'' are. And just how far the 
``have-nots'' must go to get to the top level. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, China and Norway, considered the top three  
teams in the tournament, each scored seven goals in their routs. 
The Americans connected seemingly at will against the porous 
Nigerian defense. China's speed and savvy was too much for neophyte 
Ghana. Norway ripped through Canada like a savage winter storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany and Brazil, who meet Sunday at Landover, Md., with first  
place in Group B at stake, probably are the next best among the 16 
teams. Each has a lopsided win to its credit. The Germans won 6-0 
over Mexico, which previously fell to the Brazilians 7-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia, which faced Canada today, won 5-0 over Japan in the  
middle game of its round-robin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any team has to be very good to get to the World Cup,'' U.S.  
star Mia Hamm said. ``Some of the countries with less experience 
are the ones who might have some big losses, but that doesn't 
necessarily mean they don't belong. All of these teams belong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of them might even get into the quarterfinals, which  
will be filled by this weekend's matches: China vs. Australia and 
Canada vs. Russia at East Rutherford, N.J., this afternoon; Ghana 
vs. Sweden and Norway against Japan later at Chicago later in the 
day; the United States vs. North Korea and Mexico vs. Italy at 
Foxboro, Mass., on Sunday, along with Germany-Brazil and 
Nigeria-Denmark at Landover. 
</P>
<P>
	China, Norway and Brazil already have advanced. The United  
States would have to collapse against the Koreans not to move on. 
Denmark and Mexico are the only teams out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really don't know North Korea that well,'' U.S. coach Tony  
DiCicco said of the upstarts from Asia who surprised the Danes 3-0 
Thursday. ``We'll watch them on film, and we'll put together a game 
plan. We might rest a couple of players. But we still want to come 
away with three points and reach the second round as the 
first-place team from our group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The North Koreans, who rarely venture outside their continent,  
complained about the tournament schedule. But it doesn't seem to 
have hurt them much, in view of a decent showing in a loss to 
Nigeria and the victory over Denmark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our players have done a good job in both defending and  
attacking, and individual players have done their jobs nicely,'' 
Korean coach Kim Hak Yong said. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Ryu Song II, secretary general of North Korea's Olympic  
Committee, ``We are handicapped. The American team always stays in 
the Eastern area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Koreans played in Pasadena, Calif., and Portland, Ore.,  
before making the cross-country trip to Massachusetts. The 
Americans played at Giants Stadium and Soldier Field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
