<DOCNO> APW19990626.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:35:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Star Wars' Mania Hits Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Star Wars mania has struck in Japan, where fans  
turned out in droves at theaters around the country Saturday for a 
sneak preview of the hit movie. 
</P>
<P>
	Some in costume and others toting light sabers, the movie-goers  
began lining up as early as Thursday to see ``Star Wars: Episode I 
-- The Phantom Menace'', which officially opens on July 10, more 
than five weeks after its U.S. debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a festival,'' said Yuki Nishijima, a 19-year old  
student who had been waiting seven hours for one of three 
late-night showings at the Nihon Gekijo theater in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Around him, hundreds of people sat in the theater's sweltering  
entryway, fanning themselves and passing the time with everything 
from backgammon to beer. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan, the world's second largest movie market, is home to  
legions of Star Wars fans, and the film has been heavily hyped by 
the media in the weeks leading up to its first showing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some say the space fantasy series holds a special appeal for the  
Japanese, who see it as an updated version of classic samurai 
films. 
</P>
<P>
	The first ``Star Wars'' movie was based loosely on ``The Hidden  
Fortress,'' a 1958 film about a warrior's journey by Akira 
Kurosawa, Japan's most renowned director. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realize this has sort of become a media event,'' said  
Chitose Koike, a 37-year old pianist who was waiting to see the 
sneak-preview. ``But I wanted to see it before everyone else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nihon Gekijo officials said advance ticket sales had already  
surpassed previous records for the theater. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 19:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Deal Defaults on Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The son of Feed The Children founder Larry  
Jones defaulted on nearly $1 million in a business deal that the 
Oklahoma City-based charity had financed, according to a newspaper 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunday Oklahoman said that Jones' son, Michael ``Allen''  
Jones, ran the charity's frame shop before and after the shop, 
known as Carousel Trading Ltd. and later as Tassels, Inc., was sold 
to a retired police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Jones eventually became part owner of the shop and  
personally guaranteed the debt, the Oklahoman reported. Within a 
year, he filed for personal bankruptcy and listed himself as owing 
his father's charity $950,000 for a ``business loan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't look good, I'll be the first to say that,'' Larry  
Jones told the Oklahoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokespeople for Feed The Children told The Associated Press  
that the charity did not sell the frame shop directly to Allen 
Jones, did not give any money to him and will not be harmed by the 
failure of his business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Feed The Children was protected,'' spokeswoman Emilee Truelove  
said. ``Feed The Children didn't lose any money. Feed The Children 
is not harmed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The disclosure comes on the heels of reports that employees at  
Feed The Children's office in Nashville, Tenn., apparently were 
caught taking food intended for the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Jones said he is frustrated by the negative publicity and  
that the reports have distracted him from his charity's mission -- 
feeding children. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Jones' attorney, former Attorney General Larry Derryberry,  
said Feed The Children expects to recover the full amount of the 
debt after the business' assets are sold, including inventory and 
equipment. The building in which the business operated has already 
been sold for $575,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 18:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Spurs' Big Men Unite To Win Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The season that almost wasn't turned out to  
be the year everything finally came together for the San Antonio 
Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Duncan demonstrated his dominance. David Robinson showed  
he's championship material. Proven veterans and unknown journeymen 
learned their roles and played them well. 
</P>
<P>
	The triumphant outcome for San Antonio was an NBA title captured  
Friday night at the expense of the underdog New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery Johnson, the 5-foot-11 ``Little General'' who'd been cut  
by the Spurs twice in his career, proved to be a big hero in 
decisive Game 5 at Madison Square Garden. He hit a corner jumper 
with 47 seconds left to give San Antonio its 78-77 winning margin. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Spurs arrived back in Texas on Saturday, Johnson stepped  
off the charter plane first, hoisting the team's championship 
trophy above his head and smiling at thousands of cheering fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heart is beating a thousand times a minute,'' Johnson said.  
``We love y'all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs had remained mostly straight-faced through their  
nearly two-month playoff run but celebrated wildly Friday night 
after silencing critics who'd maligned them for years as being 
soft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy for David Robinson. He's been taking a lot of flak  
throughout his career,'' guard Mario Elie said. ``I told Dave, `You 
shut everybody up, Dave. You ain't got nothing more to prove to 
anybody else.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson described the Spurs as ``a tough -- you heard me  
everybody -- tough basketball team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio secured the first NBA championship for the franchise  
and the first NBA title for a former American Basketball 
Association team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs came to San Antonio in 1973 as the former Dallas  
Chaparrals of the ABA and merged into the NBA in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, Robinson and Sean Elliott comprised the core of the  
Spurs much of the 1990s. Duncan joined the squad in the 1997-98 
season as the No. 1 draft pick from Wake Forest. 
</P>
<P>
	This year Duncan became the team's key offensive weapon as  
Robinson, the top draft pick a decade earlier, shifted his emphasis 
to defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan lost out to Utah's Karl Malone as the season's Most  
Valuable Player, but the 7-foot Spurs star was named MVP of the NBA 
Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is incredible,'' Duncan said. ``It feels so good.''  
</P>
<P>
	Spurs coach and general manager Gregg Popovich acquired veterans  
Elie, Jerome Kersey and Steve Kerr before this season to provide 
playoff grit. They didn't disappoint. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, this season looked like it might not happen  
because of the league's prolonged lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't begin until February, and the 50-game schedule was  
compressed into three months. That meant quick turnarounds between 
games and little time for practice. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio got off to a poor start, going 6-8 in February and  
stirring speculation that Popovich would be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the Spurs defeated the Houston Rockets on March 2,  
initiating a nine-game winning streak and a 31-5 stretch run that 
gave San Antonio a 37-13 record for the regular season and the top 
seed in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the postseason, the Spurs lost only one game in the first  
round to Minnesota then swept the Los Angeles Lakers and Portland 
Trail Blazers en route to the team's first trip to the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Before losing Game 3 to the Knicks in the finals, San Antonio  
mounted a 12-game playoff winning streak, the longest in one 
postseason in the NBA's 52-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning the championship and posting a 15-2 mark in the playoffs  
satisfied Robinson after years of frustration. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question in anybody's mind who the best team is.  
That's what makes me feel the best about this team,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs defeated the Knicks 4-1 in the best-of-7 series,  
overcoming some tremendous shooting by Allan Houston and Latrell 
Sprewell and taking advantage of the fact that New York was 
undermanned because of injuries to Patrick Ewing, Larry Johnson and 
Chris Childs. 
</P>
<P>
	As it did all season, San Antonio stressed defense in the  
series, especially in the final minutes Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what we talked about in every huddle for the last 10  
minutes, was that our defense was going to win this game for us,'' 
Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Next season Robinson embarks on his 11th year in the league.  
</P>
<P>
	Knowing what it's like to be a winner, he wouldn't mind another  
taste. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we continue to work at it,'' he said, ``we should get  
better and better and better.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 18:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
