<DOCNO> APW19990626.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 07:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Audit Finds Legal Aid Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An independent investigation showing that  
Legal Services Corp.'s five largest offices overstated their 
workloads has renewed Republican complaints that the agency misled 
Congress about how many people it has helped. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans first leveled the accusation two months ago when  
Legal Services -- which provides free legal help to poor Americans 
with civil cases such as tenant problems or court protection from 
domestic violence -- said a few of its local offices had overstated 
by tens of thousands the number of cases they handled in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Now a General Accounting Office draft report says that five  
other offices of the federally funded agency reported 75,000 cases 
they couldn't document. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers say they use the number of cases when deciding how  
much money the agency should receive. Republican critics of Legal 
Services said the GAO report shows case-reporting problems are more 
serious than the agency initially suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that the GAO has confirmed our suspicions of the  
significance and pervasiveness of the problem underscores the need 
to question whether they were hiding this from Congress,'' said 
Rep. Tom Latham, R-Iowa, a member of the House Appropriations 
subcommittee that oversees Legal Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Agency officials say that even with the new findings, the number  
of overstated cases is small compared with the total number of poor 
people -- more than 1.7 million -- who have been helped. They denied 
the agency was hiding anything and said that case reporting 
practices have been changed to correct the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal Services affiliates in Baltimore, Chicago, Los Angeles,  
New York and Puerto Rico overstated the number of cases they 
handled by 75,000 in 1997, according to a summary of the GAO report 
obtained by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO is the investigative and auditing arm of Congress.  
</P>
<P>
	The figure represents one-third of the 221,000 cases that the  
groups said they handled. Cases were double-counted, cases that 
should have been closed were counted as open, and cases paid for 
from nonfederal sources were included with the federal count, the 
summary said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO also found that some programs had no records to verify  
their clients' income and citizenship eligibility. Such 
documentation is required. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency is doing an internal review of case-reporting  
problems and is investigating whether any provided legal aid to 
ineligible clients, said John McKay, Legal Services president. 
</P>
<P>
	``LSC is completely committed to ensuring all congressional  
restrictions and laws are followed,'' McKay said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Legal Services gave $283 million in federal money to  
about 260 local affiliates to finance legal help for low-income 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican lawmakers asked the GAO to look into Legal Service's  
case reporting after The Associated Press reported in April that 
the agency overstated tens of thousands of cases handled in 1997. 
An AP review of five other offices among the agency's 269 regional 
programs found officials had overstated their caseload by at least 
90,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
