<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Uncle of Wanted Man Doubts Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN NICOLAS TOLENTINO, Mexico (AP) -- The police have found the  
real Rafael Resendiz Ramirez. He is not the much-sought railroad 
killing suspect, but the man's 66-year-old uncle, ailing and fed up 
with the attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``I accept that I am the uncle of the suspected railroad killer,  
whose true name is Angel Resendiz Resendiz,'' the uncle said in 
front of his cement block home. 
</P>
<P>
	The nephew is charged with two killings in Illinois and wanted  
for questioning about five more in Texas and one in Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI's 10 Most Wanted List identifies the suspect as Rafael  
Resendez-Ramirez -- a variation of Resendiz Ramirez -- but the 
reputed hobo reportedly has used many aliases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Angel, if you have committed those errors, I beg you to  
confront them as men do'' by turning himself in, Resendiz said in 
an earlier telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Resendiz said he doubts the guilt of the nephew who he said  
lived with him for 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not defending him, but who are the witnesses?'' he asked  
as a man wearing an FBI patch entered the Resendiz home to 
interview other relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Resendiz said he had been interviewed by the FBI and Mexican  
police and had received numerous calls for interviews. He said he 
hadn't seen his nephew for 27 years, since he disappeared at age 12 
from this sugar-growing town some 65 miles southeast of Mexico 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had given him up for dead,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Resendiz described his nephew as a normal boy who grew up in a  
one-room adobe house with his uncle and grandmother, played marbles 
in the dirt roads and helped work in the sugar-cane fields. 
</P>
<P>
	He isn't sure why his nephew left home.  
</P>
<P>
	He apparently ``did not want to study'' anymore. However, he  
added, ``many times kids don't understand why a parent, or someone 
who isn't a parent, hits them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Resendiz suffers from diabetes and eye trouble, but is still  
vigorous and leads the local farm cooperative. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Tribune reported Saturday that the suspect is the  
son of a farmer, Juan Reyes, and was raised by his mother until he 
was 6. However, the uncle said the boy had lived with his 
grandmother since birth, and never used his father's name. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother now reportedly lives in Ciudad Juarez, across the  
border from El Paso, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy was close to his grandmother, who has since died.  
</P>
<P>
	``My mother cried a lot because of his disappearance,'' Resendiz  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston Chronicle reported from the northern Mexico town of  
Rodeo that the suspect's common-law wife, Julieta Dominguez Reyes, 
said her husband was ``absolutely normal'' and showed no tendencies 
toward extreme violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he's the one, because he would have to be  
extremely cold and calculating,'' the newspaper quoted her as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Tribune reported it had contacted the suspect's  
mother, Virginia Resendiz de Maturino, who also said she had not 
heard from him lately. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he is full of hate, I ask God to cure him,'' she was quoted  
as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities believe he traverses the country aboard freight  
trains. A common thread is that the crimes occurred in homes near 
railroad tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI task force of more than 200 investigators is  
investigating the case. A $125,000 reward is posted for his 
capture. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
