<HEADLINE> Colorado Cyclists Win Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Mari Holden and Danny Pate, both of Colorado  
Springs, Colo., won elite road race titles Saturday at the U.S. 
Cycling Federation's National Road Cycling Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Holden pulled away on the last of eight laps over a 55-mile  
course that covered downtown and crossed the Ohio River into 
northern Kentucky. Her time of 1 hour, 57 minutes was 62 seconds 
faster than Julie Young of Sacramento, Calif. Kendra Wenzel of 
McKenzie Bridge, Ore., was 69 seconds back in third. 
</P>
<P>
	Holden has won three of the past four national time trials and  
had emphasized the elite race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to win this so bad,'' she said. ``Ever since not  
making the 1996 Olympic team, I wanted to prove to everyone that I 
could become a complete road cyclist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pate won the 19-to-22-year-old title over a similar course in  
Cincinnati last year and finished second in the elite road race. He 
won that 111-mile event Saturday in 88-degree heat and high 
humidity in 4:28. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Michael Creed led a break with about 30 miles left,  
helping position Pate for the win. Creed finished fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Derek Wilkerson, also from Colorado Springs, finished second, 52  
seconds behind Pate. 
</P>
<P>
	``After last year, I wanted to come back and win both titles,''  
Pate said. ``Knowing the course was a definite advantage.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
