<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Familiar Faces Protect Radio City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Likenesses of entertainment greats such as Frank  
Sinatra and Stevie Wonder are protecting Radio City Music Hall's 
landmark neon marquee while renovations to the famed theater 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	The marquee -- one of the building's best-known features since  
its 1932 opening -- was dismantled Friday as part of Radio City's 
extensive refurbishing. The venue's reopening is set for October. 
</P>
<P>
	While work on the marquee is under way, the midtown Manhattan  
fixture is now covered by scaffolding wrap -- huge wooden walls 
painted with some of the performers who've played Radio City. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Sinatra and Wonder, the wrap includes portraits of  
Tony Bennett, Tina Turner and the Rockettes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 07:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Aid for Aging Foster Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Foster children forced out of the system and  
into the world at age 18 would receive help for such necessities as 
housing and health care under legislation advancing in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 380-6 Friday in favor of the measure, which now  
goes to the Senate for approval. President Clinton supports the 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is expected to cost $500 million over five years and be  
paid for, in part, through savings in other government benefit 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Children removed from their homes due to abuse or neglect are  
supported by the government until age 18. About 20,000 are cut from 
the rolls annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers fear too many are unprepared to begin fully  
independent lives and end up jobless, drug-addicted, pregnant or in 
jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds don't finish high school, 61 percent lack job skills  
and 38 percent are diagnosed as emotionally disturbed, said Rep. 
Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., the House Ways and Means human resources 
subcommittee chairwoman and co-sponsor of the bill with Maryland 
Rep. Benjamin Cardin, the panel's senior Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Among its provisions, the legislation would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Provide double funding for the Independent Living Program,  
which teaches foster children such skills as how to find an 
apartment or balance a checkbook, from $70 million to $140 million 
a year to serve both younger and older children. For the first 
time, states could use some of the money to help them pay for 
housing. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow states to extend Medicaid coverage for foster children  
until age 21, at a cost of up to $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Permit foster care children to save up to $10,000, instead of  
the $1,000 now allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reduce fraud and abuse in the Supplemental Security Income  
program, which serves poor Americans with disabilities, by 
tightening eligibility. The savings would be applied to the foster 
care program. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting against the bill were Republican Reps. Christopher Cannon  
of Utah, Helen Chenoweth of Idaho, Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, Joel 
Hefley of Colorado, John Hostettler of Indiana and Ron Paul of 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1802.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
