<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles' Coppinger Stays in Majors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Gone today, here tomorrow.  
</P>
<P>
	The Baltimore Orioles on Saturday rescinded their decision to  
option pitcher Rocky Coppinger to Triple-A Rochester, less than 12 
hours after the right-hander ripped management for sending him to 
the minor leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball rules require that Coppinger must pass through  
revokable waivers to be optioned to the minors because he made his 
major-league debut more than three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we optioned him in May, we didn't need waivers. This time  
we will need waivers,'' general manager Frank Wren said. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, made after Friday night's 9-8 loss to the New York  
Yankees, also included the recall of reliever Gabe Molina. 
</P>
<P>
	Molina set up shop in Coppinger's locker Saturday morning and  
spoke about sticking around for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to be back up,'' Molina said. ``I'd like to stay up  
the rest of my career if I could,'' Molina said. 
</P>
<P>
	A half-hour later, Molina's nameplate was removed from the  
cubicle and replaced by Coppinger's. Molina was given an apology 
and whisked from the clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Now you see him, now you don't.  
</P>
<P>
	Coppinger, meanwhile, was back in the same clubhouse where he  
had a more than a few complaints about his up-and-down career with 
the Orioles. He won 10 games as a rookie in 1996 but has since 
bounced back and forth between Rochester and Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm too young for this (stuff). The manager has never been a  
fan of Rocky Coppinger and never will be,'' Coppinger said. ``He 
thinks I'm a mopup guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Ray Miller said Coppinger can fit into Baltimore's plans  
if he shows more consistency. This year he's 0-1 with a 9.19 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you get sent out, obviously there's a lot of feelings  
that come out,'' Miller said. ``He's gotten his chances. There's a 
little bit of accountability for the player -- he's pitched 15 
innings and given up 20 hits and 16 walks. It makes it a little 
tough to put him in a one-run game in the eighth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maturation takes a while. There's a lot of pressure here when  
you're a young man. The arm is there, the ability is there. That's 
why he was called up twice this year, especially after he had a 
terrible spring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coppinger planned to spend the day with his kids before getting  
a call from the Orioles to report to work. 
</P>
<P>
	After retiring all five batters he faced Saturday, Coppinger  
said, ``It's been a rollercoaster. I was 10 minutes away from going 
to the zoo, and then I end up pitching in a big-league game. It was 
a weird day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
