<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Dissidents Kept on Terror List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two dissident groups hostile to the  
governments of Iran and Sri Lanka have lost a legal bid to be 
removed from the State Department's list of terrorist 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court, in an opinion released Friday, said the  
law left the judges little room to decide whether Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright acted properly in declaring the groups 
have engaged in terrorist acts that threatened the national 
security of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge panel said it was not for the court to decide  
whether the People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran and the 
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam committed terrorist acts. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we see it, our only function is to decide if the secretary,  
on the face of things, had enough information before her to come to 
the conclusion that the organizations were foreign and engaged in 
terrorism,'' wrote Judge A. Raymond Randolph of the U.S. Court of 
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her conclusion might be mistaken, but that depends on the  
quality of the information in the reports that she received -- 
something we have no way of judging,'' he wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a group goes on the list, its bank accounts become subject  
to seizure and it becomes illegal for U.S. citizens knowingly to 
contribute financial support. 
</P>
<P>
	The law governing the list does not require the government to  
present information that would qualify as ``evidence'' in a court, 
the appeals panel said, and any classified information the 
secretary of state used in reaching a conclusion may continue to 
remain secret. 
</P>
<P>
	``That we cannot pronounce on the question does not mean that we  
must assume the secretary was right,'' the court said. ``It means 
we cannot make any assumption, one way or the other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unclassified information presented to the court said the  
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam was founded in 1976 to push for a 
separate Tamil state in Sri Lanka. According to the State 
Department, the group has used violent means, including bombing and 
political assassination, to achieve its goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The People's Mojahedin Organization is Iran's largest and most  
active Iranian dissident group, according to the State Department. 
Its primary goal is the overthrow of the Iranian government and the 
establishment of a secular republic. 
</P>
<P>
	The group was formed in the 1960s and ``its history is studded  
with anti-Western activity,'' that has included violence and 
terrorism, according to a CIA Intelligence Research Paper quoted in 
the opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	The group, which is considering an appeal to the Supreme Court,  
said in a statement the State Department's accusations ``are 
completely unfounded and solely seek to appease and placate the 
religious, terrorist dictatorship ruling Iran.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ed Towns, D-N.Y., said the department's allegations of  
terrorism were ``merely politically motivated echoes, devoid of any 
factual basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last September, 220 House members signed a statement calling on  
the administration to remove the Mojahedin Organization from the 
list of terrorist organizations. ``It was not Congress' intent that 
a legitimate opposition to the Iranian regime be included within 
that particular list of terrorist groups,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said neither group appears to have property or  
accounts in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``A foreign entity without property or presence in this country  
has no constitutional rights, under the due process clause or 
otherwise,'' it said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 19:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Political Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Publisher Steve Forbes is accusing Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush of relying on money from special interests groups to 
win the Iowa Republican straw poll Aug. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes swung though a county GOP barbecue to mingle with  
activists Saturday, but his mind was clearly on Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	A memo leaked last week showed Bush is seeking to line up 50  
prominent interest groups to commit to delivering backers to the 
straw poll, and that drew Forbes' ire. 
</P>
<P>
	The approximately 12,000 activists who show up for the poll will  
not pick any delegates, but they could narrow the field of serious 
candidates for the party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates who fare poorly could find attention hard to get and  
money scare as the contenders move closer to February caucuses than 
open the presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said Saturday that Bush's effort coupled with a big  
Washington fund-raiser last week give lie to any claim that Bush is 
an outsider. 
</P>
<P>
	``The proof is in the actions of the people around him,'' Forbes  
said. ``They're showering him with money and they're trying to have 
him win the Iowa straw poll by getting mobilized with their 
resources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander is seeking to raise $1  
million by the end of the month for the event, and former Vice 
President Dan Quayle's backers have sought to organize Indiana 
college students. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes declined to predict the backing he will get.  
</P>
<P>
	``All you can do is go all out. The key is not let it be  
hijacked by the lobbyists,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes is making his second bid for the Republican presidential  
nomination, and approaching far differently this time. While he 
relied almost exclusively on attack television in his last 
campaign, he has been working patiently for months to build a 
grass-roots organzation this time. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A veteran of Democrat Charles Schumer's  
successful 1998 Senate campaign has been chosen as press spokesman 
for first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate exploratory 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released Saturday, Mrs. Clinton said Howard  
Wolfson's experience and his knowledge of New York ``will be 
invaluable as I consider a run for the Senate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been very lucky to help (Rep.) Nita Lowey and Chuck  
Schumer and I'm very excited about the possibility of assisting 
Hillary Clinton,'' Wolfson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfson, who served as communications director for Schumer's  
winning run against three-term Republican incumbent Alfonse 
D'Amato, has been New York Rep. Nita Lowey's chief of staff since 
1995 and was her press secretary for two years before that. He took 
a leave from his job with the congresswoman from Westchester County 
to work on the Schumer campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has said she will announce her exploratory  
committee early next month as she continues to prepare for an 
expected run for the Senate seat being vacated next year by New 
York Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	She faces no major opposition for the nomination. Lowey had  
considered running for the Senate seat herself, but bowed out in 
favor of Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The race is being eyed on the Republican side by New York City  
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, among 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- The Alabama GOP is offering to help New  
York Republicans in their efforts to turn back any Senate campaign 
by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Winson Blount, the Alabama state party chairman, sent  
fund-raising letters to 10,000 party donors last week seeking 
donations from $50 to $500 ``to help our friends in New York in 
their battle with Hillary.'' Money raised also will help Republican 
candidates in Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Blount plans to deliver a check to the New York Republican  
Party, which he said needs financial help in opposing Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why? Because Bill and Hillary's liberal friends in Hollywood  
and on Broadway, the labor unions, the anti-gun lobbyists, NOW, and 
the environmental extremists are going to pump every dollar they 
have into Hillary's campaign,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We greatly appreciate their offer of support,'' said Brendan  
Quinn, executive director of the New York Republican State 
Committee. ``This is the first organized state effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the New York Democratic State Committee, Matthew  
Hiltzik, called the appeal ``very creative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All the outside money and fund raising won't change the fact  
that Democrats are right on the issues and Republicans are out of 
ideas,'' Hiltzik said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton and New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican,  
are both eyeing the Senate seat being vacated next year by Democrat 
Daniel Patrick Moynihan.	
</P>
<P>
 *John McCain 
</P>
<P>
	TILTON, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain didn't mention any of his  
Republican rivals for the GOP's 2000 presidential nomination on 
Saturday during a trip to New Hampshire, preferring to focus his 
criticism on President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Although polls put McCain far behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush,  
he has been urging his fellow Republicans to refrain from attacking 
each other. He puts no limits on attacking Clinton and Gore, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	The country needs a president who evokes pride, not shame, he  
told about three dozen breakfast customers at a Tilton, N.H., 
restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aren't you ashamed when the president of the United States  
treats the Lincoln Bedroom like Motel Six and he's the bellhop?'' 
he said. ``Are we proud when the vice president of the United 
States asks monks and nuns to commune spiritually with him for 
thousands of dollars?'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, cosponsor of a campaign finance bill that died in the  
Senate last year, said he plans a major announcement on the subject 
next week. When pressed for details, he repeated his goal of a 
comprehensive finance reform package that includes a ban on both 
labor union and corporate donations to candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he blames lawmakers, not special interest groups, for  
the undue influence such contributions produce. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain planned to head to New Hampshire's North Country on  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Elizabeth Dole    	
</P>
<P>
	LACONIA, N.H. (AP) -- If Elizabeth Dole has her way, she will be  
the next woman in the White House telling Americans to ``Just Say 
No'' to illegal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	During her latest campaign visit to the state with the earliest  
primary, the Republican presidential hopeful criticized the Clinton 
administration Saturday for missing an opportunity to fight drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole suggested President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore  
had not tackled the issue because public opinion didn't warrant it. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole has criticized the administration before for placing  
too much emphasis on public sentiment for other issues, such as the 
Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pollsters will tell you drugs are not very high on  
people's priority lists. Ladies and gentlemen, I don't get my 
passion from polling,'' Mrs. Dole told a crowd at a local 
Republican picnic. ``This is a cancer on our society. How can we 
not have it as a top priority?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has lacked the leadership that former first lady Nancy  
Reagan exhibited with her anti-drug campaign in the 1980s, Mrs. 
Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think 'Just Say No' worked, no question. In fact drug use  
went down when Nancy Reagan's program was underway. And then in 
'92, we saw a reversal,'' she later said after a tour of the 
Concord Boys and Girls Club in Concord. 
</P>
<P>
	Her experience with the Coast Guard's drug interdiction efforts  
while she was transportation secretary gave her valuable experience 
fighting the supply side of a war on drugs, Mrs. Dole said. She 
said she also would emphasize education and treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Dan Quayle    	
</P>
<P>
	MADRID, Iowa (AP) -- Former Vice President Dan Quayle said  
Saturday he will propose a dramatic expansion of the child care tax 
credit to encourage at least one parent to stay home with children. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle didn't' specify which parent, but cast the issue in terms  
of ``stay at home moms'' who he said have come under fire from 
``radical feminists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said he will deliver his proposal Monday in a speech in  
Washington, D.C., focusing on strengthening the family. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, parents can take a tax credit for child care costs  
only if a traditional day care provider is used. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Quayle's proposal, one parent can stay at home to care for  
a child and take a credit for what the day care costs would have 
been. 
</P>
<P>
	In essence, the plan would allow families to take a credit for  
services they would have paid for had both parents been working. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle didn't put a price tag on his proposal which he said  
would be only half the effort to strengthen families. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I'm trying to do is create an environment and a public  
policy that will give families more choices,'' Quayle said. ``The 
choice would be one parent staying home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle made his comments during his latest swing through Iowa in  
pursuit of the GOP presidential nomination. 

</P>
<P>
 *Pat Buchanan, Alan Keyes    	
</P>
<P>
	OVERLAND PARK, Kan. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopefuls Pat  
Buchanan and Alan Keyes tried to raise doubts Saturday about the 
strength of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's campaign despite his 
success at raising money and picking up endorsements. 
</P>
<P>
	Both spoke at news conferences prior to a Republican rally at  
Johnson County Community College. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, a former White House aide, columnist and television  
commentator, said Bush's early success is due to his famous name 
and to polls showing him beating the Democratic front-runner, Vice 
President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Simply because the Republican establishment and the Beltway  
media have designated George W. Bush the candidate of the 
Republican Party does not mean he is that candidate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe he's a globalist, as his father is, and a new world  
order man,'' Buchanan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this emperor has no clothes,'' Keyes said of the Texas  
governor. ``And I don't care who follows him around. He does not 
have grass-roots support, and he doesn't have it because he doesn't 
speak with principle. He doesn't stand with conviction for the 
things America needs to address.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes said his own message is that America is going through the  
greatest moral crisis in the nation's history. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to address that crisis and the issues involved in  
it, starting with issues like abortion, as a matter of top 
priority,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
 *John Kasich 
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush finished first in a  
presidential straw poll released Saturday at an annual convention 
of the Young Republican National Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who did not appear at the convention, got 43 percent of  
the vote. Rep. John Kasich of Ohio got repeated applause when he 
addressed the gathering Saturday night and received 23 percent in 
the straw poll, which was taken over a three-day period. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the other GOP presidential candidates reached  
double-digit support in the poll of 655 delegates. Elizabeth Dole 
was at 7 percent, Pat Buchanan got 6 percent and three candidates 
were at 4 percent: Steve Forbes, John McCain and Dan Quayle. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich invested far more time at the convention than any other  
candidate. He met the Young Republicans at a reception on Thursday, 
held a news conference and then attended a fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, who is hoping to emerge as an alternative to Bush, gave  
the keynote speech Saturday night during a dinner as the convention 
wound up. 
</P>
<P>
	His half-hour speech drew loud applause 18 times as he touched  
briefly on a wide range of issues including school choice, free 
enterprise, limited government, social security and tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the loudest rounds of applause came early on, when Kasich  
urged the Young Republicans to ``take a chance, take a risk'' and 
pursue their dreams. 
  	   	
</P>
