<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Score 11 Runs in 1st Inning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox scored 11 first-inning runs  
Saturday for the first time in 66 years. And Pedro Martinez, the 
best pitcher in baseball, was the beneficiary. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time since August 13, 1933 that the Red Sox  
have scored 11 runs in the first inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Offerman opened the inning with a double off Chicago White  
Sox starter James Baldwin. Lou Merloni singled and Brian Daubach 
homered to give Boston a 3-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	With one out, Troy O'Leary singled, Mike Stanley doubled, and  
Jason Varitek doubled to make it 5-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Baldwin got one more out but was pulled after walking Trot  
Nixon. Scott Eyre replace him and issued a walk to Offerman and a 
bases-clearing double to Merloni for an 8-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Daubach's RBI single made it 9-0 and Nomar Garciaparra finished  
the first-inning barrage with a two-run homer to give Boston an 
11-0 advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the Red Sox scored 11 in an inning was May 31,  
1998 against the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox have scored 10 or more runs in an inning a record 27  
times. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the White Sox gave up more than 10 runs was April  
2, 1998 against Texas. The most runs Chicago has allowed this 
season in one inning was eight runs on May 11 against Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
