<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Soccer Women Beat Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Elena Fomina scored twice after  
entering the game early in the second half and Russia advanced to 
quarterfinals of the Women's World Cup with a 4-1 win over Canada 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Irina Grigorieva and Olga Karasseva also scored for the Russians  
(2-1), who played a defensive game in the first half and then 
attacked to score four times in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada (0-2-1) controlled the play at times playing in front of  
a small crowd at Giants Stadium -- the same venue that attracted 
78,792 fans, a record for women's sports event in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	After Grigorieva and Fomina scored on shots from the top of the  
penalty area in the 54th and 66th minutes, respectively, the 
Canadians came close to tying the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Charmaine Hooper outjumped four other players to score on a  
header right in front of Russian goalkeeper Svetlana Petko in the 
76th minute. Two minutes later, second-half replacement Silvana 
Burtini was just wide of the right goalpost with another header. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the Canadians last chance. Fomina ran into the box and  
took a great pass from Olga Letuchova to beat goalkeper Nicci 
Wright in the 86th minute and Karasseva scored off another 
Letuchova assist in the first minute of injury time. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada, which was beaten 7-1 by Norway on Wednesday, dominated  
play in the opening 40 minutes, creating several scoring chances 
with crossing passes from the wings. 
</P>
<P>
	A cross from the right wing set up Geri Donnelly right in the  
middle of the penalty area but her shot sailed way over the 
crossbar. Tanya Franck forced Petko to make a diving save at the 
left goalpost with a shot from the right edge of the box in the 
35th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Letuchova, who just missed the corner of the net with a 40-yard  
blast in the 11th minute, had the Russians' best first-half scoring 
chance with a header in the box in the 43rd minute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
