<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 08:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dairy Fight Heads to Senate Floor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An agriculture spending bill in the Senate is  
becoming the battleground for a rancorous fight over letting groups 
of states band together to set milk prices in their region. 
</P>
<P>
	Two senators from Vermont, one of six states in the Northeast  
Dairy Compact, want to expand that alliance and create a new one in 
the South. 
</P>
<P>
	As early as this week, Sens. Patrick Leahy, a Democrat, and Jim  
Jeffords, a Republican, intend to offer their changes in an 
amendment to the spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers also are pushing to rework a new Agriculture  
Department proposal for the way the federal government sets the 
price of milk. 
</P>
<P>
	The big battle, however, is over the future of dairy compacts  
established by Congress as part of the farm reform law in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The compacts allow states to join together and set what they  
consider a ``fair price'' for fluid milk. A commission funded with 
dairy producer contributions controls the operations and 
establishes a price higher than the federal government's for the 
commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight pits lawmakers from the Midwest against colleagues in  
the Northeast and the South. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast compact -- the only one now operating -- is set to  
expire Oct. 1 unless Congress agrees to reauthorize it. Meantime, 
southern states are pushing for congressional approval to start 
their own a Southern Dairy Compact. 
</P>
<P>
	Midwest lawmakers complain that the Northeast compact frustrates  
farmers from their states who might want to sell milk in New 
England. 
</P>
<P>
	``It troubles me to contemplate killing the bill,'' said  
Democratic Sen. Herb Kohl of Wisconsin, ranking member of the 
Appropriations subcommittee on agriculture. ``However, I will do 
just that if dairy compact amendments are added to the bill while 
it's being debated on the Senate floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed amendment would expand the Northeast compact --  
which includes Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, 
Rhode Island and Vermont -- with Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, New 
York, Pennsylvania and Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan also would create a Southern group made up of Alabama,  
Arkansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South 
Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia, and West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida, Georgia, Missouri, Oklahoma, Texas and Kansas could  
join if their state legislatures agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	Both compacts would expire in 2002, when Congress is set to  
revisit the farm bill, according to the Vermont lawmakers' 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The compact has been studied, audited and sued, and despite  
what opponents may say, the compact has always come through with a 
clean bill of health,'' they wrote colleagues last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an opportunity here to give the states the right to  
help protect their farmers with no cost to federal government,'' 
the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	That is not the way opponents see it.  
</P>
<P>
	They argue compacts serve the interests of a few states while  
raising the price of a gallon of milk for consumers. Another 
concern is that overproduction of milk in compact areas would lower 
prices for Midwest producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say compacts help stabilize milk prices and protect  
producers from wild swings in the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has served as a model for the entire country,'' Leahy and  
Jeffords wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Their amendment has the support of 38 other senators, but its  
fate on the Senate floor remains uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Midwest lawmakers had written the chairman of the  
Senate Appropriations Committee, Republican Ted Stevens of Alaska, 
and the top Democrat, Robert Byrd of West Virginia. They also 
enlisted the support of the Senate Agriculture Committee chairman, 
Richard Lugar. 
</P>
<P>
	``These compacts would have a much greater potential to lower  
milk prices received by dairy farmers in non-compact areas,'' 
Lugar, R-Ind., wrote Stevens. 
</P>
<P>
	Lugar noted that the eligible compact states account for 36  
percent of national milk production and 62 percent of consumption. 
``We should strive toward the creation of national, not regional 
dairy policies.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
