<DOCNO> APW19990626.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 07:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Draws Battle Lines With GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, racing against the 2000  
political calendar, promises ``to be working right up to the very 
end'' of his term. 
</P>
<P>
	But as he draws deep battle lines with Republicans on issues as  
diverse as gun control and class size with only 19 months left in 
his presidency, he acknowledges reality: ``The closer you get to 
the election the more difficult it will be to pass anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his weekly radio address today, Clinton announced $1.2  
billion in grants to hire 30,000 teachers for the new school year -- 
a program approved by Congress with bipartisan support last year, 
when lawmakers were up for re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Clinton said, ``unfortunately there are some in  
Congress who are backing away from their commitment to reduce class 
size'' by financing a total of 100,000 new teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a promise made in an election year should be kept in  
the years when there are no elections,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president answered questions for 74 minutes Friday at a news  
conference meant to showcase his commitment to domestic issues now 
that Kosovo is no longer a preoccupation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, he is due to unveil a proposed Medicare prescription  
drug benefit, which aides will work through the weekend to 
finalize. 
</P>
<P>
	As for concerns about the billions of dollars his prescription  
benefit would cost, Clinton said, ``we should do it in a way that 
we're quite clear that it won't and can't break the bank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that he has been open since 1992 to the controversial  
idea of a means-testing requirement that links premium costs to 
beneficiaries' incomes for doctor visits and services. But The 
Washington Post reported today that Clinton has dropped that idea 
from the prescription plan in the face of strong opposition in 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The president cracked jokes and laughed at times, but thumped  
the podium and wagged his finger at other moments. On questions 
about his moral leadership and what responsibility he personally 
bears for the Washington partisanship he so decried, he adopted a 
husky, profound tone of voice. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the ``shattering effect'' of the high school shooting at  
Littleton, Colo., troubled Americans more than the Monica Lewinsky 
scandal and impeachment ordeal ever did. ``I think people are 
worried when they see ... the fabric of life still under great 
strain, in spite of the fact that we have quite a lot amount of 
prosperity,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for his legacy, ``I'll be remembered when I'm gone,'' said  
the second U.S. president ever to be impeached. ``Right now I'm not 
gone. I've got lots to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He challenged what he characterized as a do-nothing GOP-run  
Congress to approve his proposals for Medicare, Social Security, 
gun control, education, child care and campaign finance. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans pre-empted the president with a Friday morning  
appearance on the Capitol steps, showcasing their own priorities to 
bolster national security, improve education, cut taxes and 
safeguard the Social Security surplus for improving that program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ask the president: Please include tax relief in your  
agenda,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., joined by 
dozens of rank-and-file Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he intends to raise his voice into the nation's  
political debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect to be working right up to the end,'' he said. Yet, he  
acknowledged the reality that he is a lame-duck president. ``The 
closer you get to the election, the more difficult it will be to 
pass anything,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He twice praised his wife, Hillary, for her efforts on domestic  
policy, a nod to her all-but-official campaign for the Senate. And 
he defended her against criticism for using taxpayer-financed 
planes for political trips to New York, saying the first lady takes 
the issue ``seriously'' but the Secret Service dictates much of her 
travel arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Lewinsky scandal will not hurt his wife's political  
ambitions or the presidential campaign of Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``All elections are about the future and all candidates are  
judged on their own merits,'' he said. ``I think that the American 
people know the country is in good shape.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 07:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Low-Income Birth Center Gets Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Faced with an infant mortality rate more than  
twice the national average, District of Columbia officials are 
turning to certified nurse midwives to save lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Anthony Williams and other city leaders will help dedicate  
a facility Monday that could offer prenatal care at 40 to 60 
percent less cost than current Medicaid rates. The city is 
contributing $785,000 to help establish the birthing center, but 
the effort is headed by a women's health advocate from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prenatal care is in a state of some confusion in the district,  
and this is a novel approach,'' said Richard Monteilh, the director 
of the district's Department of Housing and Community Development.	   Ruth Lubic, who cofounded the Childbearing Center in the Morris 
Heights section of New York City's South Bronx in 1988, has spent 
the past five working to gain support and raise money for a similar 
facility in the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have the worst infant outcomes in the country and the  
Congress is here,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a nearly $1.5 million renovation, a long-vacant  
supermarket will house not only a birthing center, but a well-baby 
clinic, and a child care facility. Job training and substance abuse 
services for women also will also be offered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good for the neighborhood,'' said Bernard Richardson, the  
district's neighborhood commissioner for the area. ``We have a lot 
of young teenagers having kids who need the care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The District of Columbia's infant mortality rate is 14.9 deaths  
per 1,000 live births -- the worst in the nation. According to 
figures released by the Annie E. Casey Foundation's Kids Count 
survey, more than 14 percent of the babies born in the district are 
low birth-weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Lubic said other organizations are working to establish similar  
family service operations in Atlanta, Nashville and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The D.C. Developing Families Center will begin offering prenatal  
care through an agreement with Howard University Hospital by 
September. Within six months, women will also have the option of 
delivering at Howard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
