<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC: Media Probe To Avoid Censorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Better self-regulation by the  
entertainment industry -- and not government censorship -- will 
improve efforts to shield children from harmful depictions of 
violence, said the head of the Federal Trade Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``First and foremost, we will not judge the content of these  
products,'' Robert Pitofsky said Friday in a speech at a national 
convention of District Attorneys General. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not the modern embodiment of the thought police, and we  
don't want to be,'' Pitofsky said. ``Our goal is to work with -- not 
against -- the entertainment industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, President Clinton ordered the FTC and  
Justice Department to investigate whether -- and how -- the 
entertainment business markets violence to children. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 million review is due in 18 months, but Pitofsky said he  
anticipates a report will be ready within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitofsky said improved policing by entertainment companies of  
their own products is the goal. And he makes no apologies to 
critics who call that a ``cop out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen industry self-regulation work in industries as  
divergent in economic terms as the advertising industry and the 
funeral directors,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton called for the study in the wake of a deadly spate of  
school shootings. He said children ``are being fed a dependable 
daily dose of violence'' that amounts to witnessing 40,000 deaths 
by their 18th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a barrage blurs the line between fantasy and reality  
violence for too many children, the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer Granholm, a prosecutor from Michigan, said she expects  
the study to find ``explicit marketing to children of extremely 
violent video games, movies, etc.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She offered Pitofsky her state as a testing ground if a lawsuit  
is deemed necessary to stop such marketing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
