<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Budget a Target for Pruning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Blending the tactics of a presidential  
campaign with a marketing pitch out of corporate America, an 
alliance of business leaders is trying to reorder the federal 
budget to cut defense spending in favor of education, health care 
and other needs. 
</P>
<P>
	It is an unlikely mission for big business executives, easily  
labeled as part of the military-industrial complex that pushes 
defense budgets and benefits from weapons contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	But more than 400 corporate leaders, retired military officers  
and former government officials have signed on with Business 
Leaders for Sensible Priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not peaceniks,'' says Ben Cohen, the Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice  
cream man who is the president and the major donor to the 
organization. ``We are businessmen and military types.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Organizations bent on pruning defense spending are nothing new.  
And the debate about budget priorities between military and 
domestic needs has been going on for decades, especially the last 
one, since the fall of the Soviet Union and the end of the Cold 
War. 
</P>
<P>
	This debate claims to be different because it isn't coming at  
the issue from the left, although there certainly are liberals on 
its roster. Leaders of the group say that its members and support 
come from across the political spectrum, that even boardroom 
conservatives want to do something about defense spending they 
consider wasteful. 
</P>
<P>
	It also is different for the way it is trying to change minds,  
not by lobbying inside the Beltway but by campaigning outside. 
Cohen said the budget for that campaign will be $3 million this 
year, $6 million next. 
</P>
<P>
	And the first target is Iowa, where Cohen said there will be  
television ads comparable to those of the candidates competing for 
the opening caucuses of the 2000 campaign next winter. The group 
plans to spend about $800,000 to make its issue seen and heard 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said the organization has six staffers in the state now.  
It also is going to be the scene of a showy bus tour, with street 
theater, music and giant, inflatable visual aids on the way federal 
money is being spent. And as an added attraction, free ice cream. 
</P>
<P>
	Essentially, the organization is trying to market an issue  
instead of a product or a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Their case is that without a Cold War, the United States still  
has a Cold War defense budget. ``We are now, literally, in an arms 
race with ourselves,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their blueprint for changing that was drawn by Lawrence Korb, an  
assistant secretary of defense in the Reagan administration, in an 
alternative budget that would cut Pentagon spending by $48 billion 
without, he says, diminishing needed capabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	But Congress, and the administration, are going in the opposite  
direction, increasing defense spending. The House has just approved 
nearly $290 billion for defense next year. That's $1.4 billion more 
than the increased budget President Clinton recommended. There's 
more to come for peacekeeping forces in Kosovo -- $1.5 billion to $2 
billion a year by administration estimate, twice that according to 
outside analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's defense budget seeks an increase of $112 billion over  
the next five years, to $319 billion in 2005. Republicans in 
Congress said it wasn't enough. And that was before the bombing 
campaign against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	That is not a promising setting for another effort to reduce  
Pentagon spending. But the leaders of Business Leaders for Sensible 
Priorities say theirs is not just another effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Their backing, background and techniques make this one  
different, they say. They believe they can put their issue on the 
public agenda, using professional market research, paid 
advertising, public relations and other corporate tools to mobilize 
opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	To do all that, they are going to have to create a market. There  
is no sign now of a national mood favoring defense cuts. When 
Clinton proposed increasing the defense budget, the polls found 
that a majority agreed with him. Cuts aren't a topic in the 2000 
presidential campaign; increases are. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
