<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SunJet Unexpectedly Cancels Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) -- The discount travel service SunJet  
International canceled all its flights without explanation, leaving 
ticket-holders without rides to a half-dozen cities. 
</P>
<P>
	A recorded message on SunJet's toll-free telephone line Saturday  
said it also was no longer taking reservations and promised 
would-be passengers a refund within seven days. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's Web site still advertised charter flights  
connecting Detroit and Newark, N.J., and connecting Newark with the 
Florida cities of Fort Lauderdale, Orlando, Tampa-St. Petersburg 
and West Palm Beach for fares starting at $79. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, operated as a public charter by World Technology  
Systems, had arranged flights connecting the cities since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no comment from the company on the cause of the  
cancellation, its financial status or how many passengers had been 
booked when the shutdown was announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Repeated calls to SunJet's headquarters in Smyrna, an Atlanta  
suburb, were not returned Friday or Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 100 people showed up Friday morning at Fort  
Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport for a $79 flight to 
Newark. They were twice told the flight would be delayed, and late 
in the afternoon a sign was posted saying all flights had been 
canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration had no information on  
SunJet, said spokeswoman Katherine Creedy. She said her agency 
monitors airlines, but not charter travel companies such as SunJet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
