<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- The party headed by a former military  
leader chose a former presidential candidate on Saturday to make a 
second run in the Nov. 7 presidential elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfonso Portillo Cabrera, a 47-year-old attorney, was chosen at  
a Guatemalan Republican Front assembly presided over by retired 
Gen. Efrain Rios Montt, who took power in a March 1982 coup and was 
overthrown in another coup in August 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The Front is the first party to choose a candidate for the  
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Rios Montt's efforts to win election as president have been  
blocked by a constitutional clause against former coup leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Portillo vowed to review the privatization of state companies  
and ``prosecute those responsible'' for any irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's sale of the state telephone and electrical  
companies have been controversial. 
</P>
<P>
	Portillo was the Front's candidate in the 1995 elections, which  
were won by Alvaro Arzu of the National Advance Party. 
</P>
<P>
	If no candidate wins 51 percent of the vote on Nov. 7, a second  
round between the top two finishers would be held on Dec. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A woman regarded as Mexico's most colorful  
politician said she will quit an opposition party to support a 
ruling party candidate for president, newspapers reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Irma Serrano, who has been among the most ferocious critics  
of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, was 
quoted as saying she was ``disappointed'' with Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, 
leader of her Democratic Revolution Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers reported that she will join the PRI to support the  
presidential campaign of former Tabasco Gov. Roberto Madrazo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cardenas has changed and has taken a weak and fearful attitude  
to the system,'' she was quoted as saying by the daily Cronica. ``I 
am going to fight alongside those who do not fear the system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serrano, a former actress and singer known as The Tigress, also  
is famous as the former mistress of several prominent politicians, 
including former President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
