<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Security Upgraded at 6 US Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- All six U.S. embassies in Africa closed  
because of terrorism concerns received security upgrades after the 
bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania in 1998, the 
State Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The embassies in Gambia, Togo, Madagascar, Liberia, Namibia and  
Senegal were temporarily closed Thursday after suspicious 
individuals had conducted surveillance at the site, the State 
Department said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	American embassies worldwide are on heightened alert due to  
increased security concerns, including U.S. intelligence suspicions 
that Osama bin Laden, an exiled Saudi millionaire, was in the final 
stages of planning a terrorist attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen a pattern of activity indicating continued  
planning for terrorist attacks by members of Osama bin Laden's 
network,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said. ``And we 
take reporting of such threats seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A decision will be made over the weekend on whether to reopen  
the six shuttered embassies in Africa on Monday, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden, who is on the FBI's 10 most-wanted list, is accused  
of masterminding the Aug. 7, 1998, attacks on the U.S. embassies in 
Kenya and Tanzania, which killed a total of 224 people, including 
12 Americans. He and nine of 15 suspects on trial in New York 
remain fugitives. 
</P>
<P>
	With the bombing anniversary on the horizon, U.S. officials are  
stepping up vigilance, although some critics say security 
precautions have gone too far. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you close six embassies in a region in the world, you  
send a message to the world that not only have the terrorists made 
us blink but we have written off a large number of people in a part 
of the world,'' said Harvey Kushner, chairman of the Criminal 
Justice Department at Long Island University's C.W. Post campus. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the twin bombings, security at many U.S. embassies  
worldwide, including the six in Africa, has been improved by adding 
physical barriers, installing video cameras and building walls, 
fences and barricades, the State Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of local guards has increased and embassies have  
worked with the host countries to close streets or change traffic 
patterns. Property surrounding embassies was acquired in some 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The State department has added 140 special security agent jobs  
overseas and temporarily sent hundreds of diplomatic security 
officers to foreign posts. U.S. officials also are moving to hire 
and train 200 new diplomatic security agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, all of the closed embassies -- except in Banjul,  
Gambia, and Windhoek, Namibia -- received security upgrades in the 
mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	A commission chaired by retired Adm. Bobby Inman recommended  
better embassy protection after bombings at embassy sites in Beirut 
and Kuwait in 1983 and 1984 that killed a total of more than three 
dozen Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Gambia, the embassy is a cultural center and the residence  
of the U.S. ambassador. It is located in Fajara, a suburb of the 
capital, Bajul. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Togo, the embassy is located at an intersection. A guard  
stationed outside its gates said already tight security had not 
been beefed up. 
</P>
<P>
	--In the Senegalese capital of Dakar, the embassy is located in a  
bustling downtown. Gendarmes cordoned off three streets surrounding 
the building. 
</P>
<P>
	American embassies have been closed before in response to  
terrorist threats or concerns they might be targeted. Most U.S. 
embassies in sub-Saharan Africa were ordered closed for two days in 
December, following U.S. military strikes on Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., urged Congress to  
complete action on the State Department appropriations bill that 
provides $583.5 million to improve embassy security. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregg, chairman of a Senate Appropriations subcommittee, added  
$105 million in security money to the administration's request for 
embassies. ``The sudden closing of six U.S. embassies in Africa 
yesterday underscores the need to improve security overseas for our 
personnel and facilities,'' he said Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
