<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. Gov. Praises GOP Colleagues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- The average American worked 173 days this  
year to cover the cost of taxes and government regulation, but 
Republican governors are reducing that burden, Michigan Gov. John 
Engler said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Engler used the Republican Party's weekly radio address to  
praise the efforts of the 31 GOP governors to cut taxes and improve 
education and government. 
</P>
<P>
	``My colleagues ... are cutting taxes and reducing the size of  
government,'' Engler said in the address, taped Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``And just as important, GOP governors are reforming welfare and  
fixing our public schools so taxpayers get more for their money, 
more families can escape poverty and more children can get a 
high-quality education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, the average American had to work until July 2 to  
cover taxes and the cost of government regulation, Engler said. He 
noted that the date this year fell on June 22, crediting Republican 
governors with shortening the time period by 11 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Engler also took a dig at President Clinton's wife, Hillary, who  
is considering running as Democratic candidate for the Senate from 
New York, a state where Engler said Republican Gov. George Pataki 
has signed 36 tax cuts into law. 
</P>
<P>
	``As Governor Pataki puts it, New York has gotten so much better  
with Republican leadership, first lady Hillary Clinton is thinking 
of moving there,'' Engler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among GOP successes, Engler mentioned the income and business  
tax cuts he has pushed through in Michigan this year, as well as an 
income tax cut promoted by Colorado Gov. Bill Owens and a phase-out 
of the Virginia personal property tax by Gov. Jim Gilmore. 
</P>
<P>
	Engler also boasted of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush's efforts to set  
higher education standards for students and teachers, and praised 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's efforts to boost teacher salaries and 
set up an early intervention program to make sure all children 
become good readers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether the issue is fixing our children's schools, fighting  
crime or facing down the special interests who want to grow 
government, Republican governors are making a difference in the 
lives of average American families,'' Engler said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
