<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Broadcaster To Have Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Cubs radio broadcaster Ron Santo will  
undergo heart bypass surgery Monday at Northwestern Memorial 
Hospital in Chicago, team officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former third baseman for the Cubs suffered a mild heart  
attack last Monday and admitted himself into a Denver hospital. He 
was in Colorado to broadcast the Cubs' three-game series with the 
Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Since returning to Chicago on Thursday, Santos has been  
receiving treatment at Northwestern Memorial. It was unclear 
whether Santo would remain in the hospital over the weekend, a Cubs 
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	A hospital spokeswoman referred all questions about Santo to the  
Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Santo, a nine-time All-Star and five-time Gold Glove winner,  
became the team's radio announcer 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Santo, 59, has a history of diabetes and recently underwent an  
angiogram that revealed a minor blockage of one artery. 
</P>
<P>
	While Santo recovers, his commentator's job in the radio booth  
is being handled by Randy Hundley, Santo's former teammate on the 
Cubs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
