<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Top Prospects for NBA Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Top players in Wednesday's NBA draft, by position:  
</P>
<P>
                             *Centers    	
</P>
<P>
	--Aleksandar Radojevic, 7-foot-3, Barton (Kan.) CC. A true  
project who would have benefited from a season or two at Ohio 
State, but the NCAA ruled him ineligible. He'll be spending a lot 
of time in the weight room and in one-on-one teaching situations in 
the next couple of years. 
</P>
<P>
	--Todd MacCulloch, 7-0, Washington. The Canadian native led the  
nation in field goal percentage the last three seasons, finishing 
at 66 percent for his career. Obviously, solid down low; his open 
court speed is his biggest detriment. 
</P>
<P>
	--Calvin Booth, 6-11, Penn State. A true shot-blocker who led the  
Big Ten at 3.5 per game last season. Has long arms, and his great 
patience kept him out of foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Power Forwards    	
</P>
<P>
	--Elton Brand, 6-8, Duke. The consensus national player of the  
year can cause matchup problems with his strength down low and an 
impressive offensive arsenal that includes a very solid jump shot. 
If he continues to improve as he did in his two years at Duke he 
could be a star in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	--Jonathan Bender, 6-11, Picayune, Miss. He made a name for  
himself by breaking Michael Jordan's scoring record in the 
McDonald's All-America game, but he has a lot more to offer. Scouts 
praise his defense as well as his offense, which includes a solid 
jump shot. He may end the run of high school players who didn't get 
much run. 
</P>
<P>
	--Lee Nailon, 6-9, Texas Christian. Pulled his name out of the  
draft last year and returned to school but didn't have a great 
senior season. Still, he's a good scorer in the post, and having 
played for Billy Tubbs he is comfortable in an uptempo offense. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Small Forwards    	
</P>
<P>
	--Lamar Odom, 6-10, Rhode Island. One college season was enough  
to see how talented and versatile this New York native is. He may 
start his pro career as a small forward, but his skills point 
toward a long future at shooting guard and plenty of time at the 
point as well. His ``I'm in-I'm out'' last-minute attitude toward 
the draft won't scare anyone away. 
</P>
<P>
	--Wally Szczerbiak, 6-8, Miami, Ohio. Probably the most mature  
player in the draft, Wally World, came up big in every big 
situation as a senior, from the Goodwill Games where he banged with 
bigger guys, to the NCAA tournament, where he scored 43 points 
against Washington, to the predraft camps, where he left a lot of 
open mouths with 3-point shooting shows. 
</P>
<P>
	--James Posey, 6-8, Xavier. One of those quiet, solid types whom  
fans know and coaches covet. He's a ferocious rebounder and very 
quick. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Shooting Guards    	
</P>
<P>
	--Richard Hamilton, 6-6, Connecticut. A true scorer who can shoot  
squaring up or on the break. He goes to the basket pretty well, 
too. A little on the lean side, but he made it through the Big East 
and its man-to-man style, so he must be tougher than most. The wait 
for him in the weight room will be worth it. 
</P>
<P>
	--Trajan Langdon, 6-6, Duke. A pure shooter who goes as deep as  
you need, as proven by his exhibition from the 25-foot range 
against Temple's zone in the NCAA tournament. He has to learn to 
get his own shot, but he still would be a great situational pick. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kris Clack, 6-5, Texas. He was a standout in Tom Penders'  
run-and-gun style with the Longhorns then showed he can play 
defense and still score at a slower pace under Rick Barnes. 
</P>
<P>
                           *Point Guards    	
</P>
<P>
	--Steve Francis, 6-3, Maryland. In his one year with the  
Terrapins he led the world in highlight clips. He is one of those 
special talents who can also make others better, and his quickness 
makes him a good defender. It won't be long before kids in parks 
are imitating his crossover first step. 
</P>
<P>
	--Baron Davis, 6-3, UCLA. What scares teams is the major knee  
surgery he had after his freshman season. What impresses them is 
his sophomore season when he showed the same explosiveness and 
attitude as the year before. No player in the draft has as much 
on-court confidence as Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	--Andre Miller, 6-2, Utah. A four-year college player who is as  
solid as they come. If a team needs flash it will pass on Miller. 
If a team needs a mature winner it will find a way to draft him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 08:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Counsels and Probes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A list of independent counsels and their investigations since  
1978, the year Congress enacted the law that empowered them: 
</P>
<P>
	--Arthur H. Christy, appointed in 1979 to investigate charges  
that Hamilton Jordan, chief of staff to President Jimmy Carter, 
used cocaine. No indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gerald Gallinghouse, appointed in 1980 to investigate charges  
of cocaine use by Tim Craft, Carter's campaign manager. No 
indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Leon Silverman, appointed in 1981 to investigate charges of  
Mafia ties by Raymond J. Donovan, President Reagan's labor 
secretary. No indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Jacob A. Stein, appointed in 1984 to investigate charges of  
financial improprieties by Attorney General Edwin Meese III. No 
indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Whitney North Seymour Jr., appointed in 1986 and won perjury  
conviction of Michael K. Deaver, Reagan's deputy chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	--Alexia Morrison, appointed in 1986 to investigate accusations  
that former Assistant Attorney General Theodore Olson deceived 
Congress. No indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Lawrence E. Walsh, appointed in 1986 to investigate Reagan  
administration's sale of weapons to Iran and diversion of profits 
to Nicaraguan rebels. Obtained convictions, some overturned on 
appeal; others led to pardons by President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	--James C. McKay, appointed in 1987, won conviction of Lyn  
Nofziger, Reagan's White House political director, for committing 
ethics violations in lobbying later in his career. Conviction 
overturned on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	--Carl Rauh and James Harper, appointed for an investigation that  
began in 1987 of the finances of Lawrence Wallace, a former 
assistant attorney general. No indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--1989, name of counsel and target sealed. No indictments.  
</P>
<P>
	--Arlin M. Adams and Larry D. Thompson, appointed in 1990, to  
investigate sale of favors in the Department of Housing and Urban 
Development. Several indictments and convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	--1991, name of counsel and target sealed. No indictments.  
</P>
<P>
	--Joseph DiGenova, appointed in 1992 to investigate charges of  
abuse of passport files by the Bush Administration. No indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Robert B. Fiske Jr. and Kenneth Starr, for an inquiry opened in  
1994 into President and Hillary Rodham Clinton's Whitewater land 
deal. Investigation led to the president's impeachment for perjury 
and obstruction stemming from his relationship with Monica 
Lewinsky. The Senate acquitted him Feb . 12. 
</P>
<P>
	--Donald C. Smaltz, appointed in 1994, won an indictment of  
former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, on charges of receiving 
gifts and entertainment from companies or organizations regulated 
by the Agriculture Department. Espy was later acquitted. 
</P>
<P>
	--David M. Barrett, appointed in 1995, won the indictment of  
former housing secretary Henry G. Cisneros on charges that he lied 
about payments to a former mistress. Trial set for September. 
</P>
<P>
	--Daniel S. Pearson, appointed in 1995 to investigate Commerce  
Secretary Ronald H. Brown's finances. The investigation ended with 
Brown's death in a plane crash in Croatia in April 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	--Curtis Emery von Kann, appointed in 1996 to investigate Eli  
Segal for charges of conflict of interest in fund raising for a 
private group while he was head of the Americorps program. No 
indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Carol Elder Bruce, appointed in 1998, to investigate whether  
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt lied to Congress about his role in 
rejecting a proposal from a group of Wisconsin Indians for a 
casino. Pending. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ralph I. Lancaster Jr., appointed in 1998, to investigate  
accusations that Labor Secretary Alexis Herman engaged in influence 
peddling and solicited $250,000 in illegal campaign contributions. 
Pending. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990626.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 10:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Convicted of Giving Girl AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- A man accused of having sex with a  
13-year-old girl and giving her the virus that causes AIDS was 
convicted of felonious assault. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now 14, said that Henry Couturier, 47, did not tell  
her he had the virus when they had sex in May 1998. She tested 
positive for HIV about three months later. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys argued the girl was a prostitute who could  
have contracted the virus from a customer. They also said Couturier 
told her he was HIV-positive and that he had used a condom every 
time he had sex with her. 
</P>
<P>
	Couturier was also convicted Friday on three counts of  
corruption of a minor and corruption with drugs. Sentencing is 
scheduled for July 28. Couturier faces up to 14 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Todd W. Barstow said he will urge Couturier to  
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl had been convicted last year of a delinquency count of  
soliciting for prostitution and admitted working as a prostitute. 
She testified that she didn't know how many men she had sex with 
before Couturier. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
