<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormons Emphasizing Child Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Candidates seeking entrance into the  
Mormon church's temples will now be asked if they are keeping up 
with child support. 
</P>
<P>
	The change underscores a growing concern of leaders in The  
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints about divorce among 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we see increasing strains on families everywhere, church  
leaders have felt it necessary to place additional emphasis on 
meeting all family responsibilities and obligations,'' Mormon 
officials said in a prepared statement this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Members are interviewed before receiving temple ``recommends''  
which deem them worthy to participate in the most sacred 
proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	While a question about child support has been asked since 1985,  
new changes in the wording specifically ask: ``Do you have 
financial or other obligations to a former spouse or children? If 
yes, are you current in meeting those obligations?'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the old wording, members were first asked if they had been  
divorced or separated. Only if the answer was yes did the questions 
go on to determine if candidates were current in financial 
obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	AMCAP president Lane Fischer said 1999's emphasis on child  
support is important, because the church can help establish a 
standard of behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want this privilege and this blessing to go to the  
temple, then this is the expectation, just like paying tithing or 
being morally honest,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
