<DOCNO> APW19990626.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 08:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Gadfly Attacks Council Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHINCOTEAGUE, Va. (AP) -- ``Facts are fine, fer as they go, but  
they're like water bugs skittering atop the water.'' So said 
Grandpa Beebe, the late local sage. ``Legends, now they go deep 
down and bring up the heart of a story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What started as a search for some facts -- uncomfortable ones, to  
be sure -- is turning into the stuff of legend in this normally 
laid-back island town. The tale folks will tell for years has the 
requisite ``bad guys,'' the moment of comeuppance, and, of course, 
the unlikely hero. 
</P>
<P>
	The latter is local boat dealer Charlie Kambarn, the guy who got  
the whole thing stirred up. ``It's really turned into something 
next to a circus,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Till now, this Eastern Shore town of 3,500 was best known for  
the volunteer fire company's wild pony swim and auction, an annual 
event that gave rise to Marguerite Henry's ``Misty'' books. But now 
even Jay Leno's calling to hear about the homegrown scandal that 
cost the mayor, town manager and police chief their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	It all started in March, when some of the city fathers went to  
Orlando, Fla., for a conference on hurricanes, a subject of great 
interest to a coastal island in the Atlantic's hurricane alley. No 
sooner had Mayor Harry S. Thornton, Town Manager T. Stewart Baker 
and Police Chief Willis Dize returned than rumors started flying 
about Hooters dinners and Crown Royal lunches. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter Charlie Kambarn.  
</P>
<P>
	At 48, with thinning hair, speckled green eyes and a ruddy  
complexion, this youngest son of a famously frugal father has 
earned a reputation as a likable playboy. He has a diamond cluster 
and two other gold rings glinting from his fingers. On an island of 
rugged fishermen, he'd rather use his green-and-white Sea Ray to 
troll the tiki bars along the shore than to fish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I eat my tuna out of a can,'' he says with a laugh as he blows  
smoke from a White Owl Miniature through the sunroof of his gold 
Lexus. ``I couldn't make a living working on the water.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kambarn hadn't been to a city council meeting in 10 years. He  
swears he'd never spoken in public before. But when he heard about 
the spending spree -- which came on the heels of the council's 20 
percent water rate hike -- he wanted information. 
</P>
<P>
	When he didn't get it, he started filing Freedom of Information  
requests. City officials tried to discourage Kambarn with 
photocopying fees -- $1,300 in all. OK, he said, and he paid. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Kambarn's persistence paid off with a trail of credit  
card receipts that set the townsfolk on their ears. 
</P>
<P>
	A $364 bar tab from the Orlando hotel pool.  
</P>
<P>
	A $319 bill for dinner at Charlie's Lobster House (the tip alone  
was $42). 
</P>
<P>
	And $420 for a rental car that took the officials to Key West,  
hundreds of miles away, during some of the conference's most 
important sessions -- evacuation routes, shelter management, rescue 
and recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance at council meetings swelled from the usual dozen to a  
couple hundred. When it was all over, Chief Dize was fired, manager 
Baker had resigned and a judge suspended Mayor Thornton pending 
further review. The latter two have declined comment. Dize's 
attorney says his client wasn't given a fair hearing and will sue 
if not reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Folks in town are divided about all of this.  
</P>
<P>
	The locals don't begrudge a little financial latitude on these  
trips, says Donald Leonard, a former councilman. But for a town 
with a budget of $3 million, he says, this looked like ``raw 
extravagance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a couple of glasses of booze on the town,'' the  
73-year-old retired motel operator says. ``I don't think most 
people in town are opposed to two or three drinks with dinner. I 
think they oppose sitting around the bar and running up a $300 
tab.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some see another factor at work here. No one cared much to check  
on public expenditures, they say, until it came time to choose a 
location for the island's new bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of state Highway 175, a 50-year-old swing bridge  
crosses Chincoteague Sound and gently drops vehicles into downtown, 
right between the Roxy Theater and Bill's Restaurant, where Dize 
and a group of old-timers gather for coffee and cigarettes every 
morning and afternoon. But the state said the bridge needs 
replacing and asked city and county officials for a recommendation 
on one of two options. 
</P>
<P>
	One location for the $30 million span would be to the north of  
the old bridge. The other would funnel traffic toward the south end 
of town -- and smack-dab into the beloved two-story brick firehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Mason says the skinny around town was that the council  
supported the southern bridge, as she does. She says getting rid of 
the three officials was ``a way to circumvent it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A short blond woman with bare shoulders and big hoop earrings,  
she went to school with Kambarn and resents the implication that 
her being in favor of the southern bridge is a vote against the 
firemen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fire company, that's used as a whip,'' says Mason, owner  
of the Waterside Motor Inn. ``If you're against the fire company, 
that's like the American flag and Mom's apple pie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She doesn't condone the spending spree but hates what the  
scandal and the bridge fight have done to her town. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like this divisiveness,'' she says. ``We love where we  
live. We all have that common denominator. ... Why would we want to 
change that to where none of us would want to live here anymore?'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Kambarn, he got his $1,300 back -- and a whole lot more  
attention than he bargained for. 
</P>
<P>
	His stock in trade is Johnson marine motors, but he's been too  
busy to get much grease under his nails lately. He's talked to lots 
of reporters -- but not to Leno. That would be ``like making a 
mockery of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People were coming in my office, calling me, thanking me,''  
says Kambarn. ``My son says I'm starting to SOUND like a 
politician.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some wish he'd left well enough alone. ``I've lost some friends  
over this,'' he says. ``Some people don't even nod their head to me 
anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He still thinks he only did what needed to be done.  
</P>
<P>
	``All I did was ask for a little information.''  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Allen G. Breed is the AP's Southeast regional  
writer, based in Raleigh, N.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
